SP  - 497
EP  - 502
DO  - 10.1109/ICSECS65227.2025.11278921
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105032644902&doi=10.1109%2FICSECS65227.2025.11278921&partnerID=40&md5=ad1cbe36a8a7332c1a372ce04294f43d
AB  - —Automated surface defect classification in steel manufacturing is essential to meet increasing global demands and improve inspection efficiency. While Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) have shown promising results, their reliance on local surfaces and large labeled datasets limits their effectiveness for complex defects detection and classification. This study investigates the performance of a Vision Transformer (ViT) compared to several Convolutional Neural Network models using the NEU hot rolled steel surface defect dataset. Performance was evaluated using accuracy, confusion matrices, ROC-curves, Grad-CAM visualization and training behavior. In the investigation, Swin ViT achieved perfect classification accuracy but exhibited signs of overfitting, suggesting a need for optimization techniques such as learning rate scheduling. CNN models like MobileNet, InceptionV3, and VGG16 performed competitively with high accuracy and better generalization, while EfficientNetB0 failed to learn significant features. The result indicates that both ViT and CNNs have distinct strengths, with Swin ViT excelling in accuracy and CNNs offering stable training. Future work will explore additional models, datasets, and training parameter tuning to enhance robustness and generalizability. ©2025 IEEE.
